@sanatmpa1 ,
I was able to reproduce the issue in tf 2.7, 2.5 and nightly.Please find the gist of it [here](https://colab.research.google.com/gist/tilakrayal/02292fbc8236872182b34be86936b511/53345.ipynb).

@frgfm 

I modified dtype in model_output to tf.float32 and I can see that no error is thrown. Please find the [gist here](https://colab.sandbox.google.com/gist/sanatmpa1/3b6fb0a9a1ea76f324661dee6238fde3/53345.ipynb). Thanks!

Hi @sanatmpa1, thanks for the reply!

However, I'm not sure I follow here: the reason why I create the model output in `tf.float16` is because that's what comes out of keras model in this dtype_policy (at least in my short experience with mixed precision in TF). So are you suggesting to cast the model output to float32 before sending it to the loss?

If so, shouldn't users be able to use this policy without modifying their internal loss computation? (I was expecting the loss to perform those operations internally if necessary considering I set the dtype_policy globally)
If not, would you mind elaborating a bit please? :pray:

Generally when you set the Mixed precision dtype policy to float16, it uses float16 for computations and float32 for variables in-order to bring the numeric stability. 
You can try printing the below lines to validate.
```
print('Compute dtype: %s' % policy.compute_dtype)
print('Variable dtype: %s' % policy.variable_dtype)
```
Refer [this](https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/mixed_precision) document for more details.
This issue has been automatically marked as stale because it has no recent activity. It will be closed if no further activity occurs. Thank you.

> Generally when you set the Mixed precision dtype policy to float16, it uses float16 for computations and float32 for variables in-order to bring the numeric stability. You can try printing the below lines to validate.
> 
> ```
> print('Compute dtype: %s' % policy.compute_dtype)
> print('Variable dtype: %s' % policy.variable_dtype)
> ```
> 
> Refer [this](https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/mixed_precision) document for more details.

Hi @sachinprasadhs,

I'm not sure I understand how it's related to my previous comment :thinking:
Simply put: if mixed precision policy is used, the CTC loss crashes. My snippet above is reproducing this error, because the CTC doesn't support float16.

So there are 2 questions here:
- is this normal that this loss doesn't support float16?
- if it is, how should one use this? I understand quite well that variables are in fp32 and operations in fp16, but I guess that still means that it's normal for the model output to be in fp16. And in that case, I would argue that some additional information should be added to document the usage.

Refer to [this](https://github.com/keras-team/keras/blob/83bee297d7176beb6ed197963669b0dd55acea0c/keras/mixed_precision/policy.py#L262) compute_dtype code of mixed_precision_policy and the explanation below that, hope it clarifies your above question. Thanks!

Hi @sachinprasadhs !

Thanks, but I still think there is something missing here: the way the operations are handled internally is not an issue. Here I didn't write a custom loss function.

The problem is:
- using the mixed precision policy, my model output logits comes in `tf.float16` (which is expected)
- I used the official TF ctc_loss. So this takes as arguments a tensor in `tf.float16` (because of the mixed precision policy mentioned just above), which is also logical/expected
- but here the loss doesn't accept that data type

So either:
- I missed something in the doc saying "You have to cast any args to `tf.float32` for the CTC loss" :man_shrugging: 
- or this is an issue that hasn't been handled

@frgfm, as a workaround until this bug is fixed, you can cast the model output (the second argument to ctc_loss) to float32 before passing it to `tf.nn.ctc_loss`. The [mixed precision guide](https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/mixed_precision) also recommends this, mostly because numeric issues can occur if the tensor flowing between a softmax and cross entropy loss is in float16, but also due to issues where losses do not support float16 or have numeric issues with float16. All built-in losses should support float16 though, so this is bug.

/CC @nluehr @benbarsdell, the errors come from the fact float32 tensors are created, followed by dtype mismatches on [this line](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/8f761b623768c5ed59a502d7eff35cc0c3bccb16/tensorflow/python/ops/ctc_ops.py#L591) and [this line](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/8f761b623768c5ed59a502d7eff35cc0c3bccb16/tensorflow/python/ops/ctc_ops.py#L595). Do you think we should fix these individual dtype mismatches, or just have `ctc_loss` cast its inputs to float32 and outputs back to float16? I don't understand how ctc loss works, but it has a lot of reductions and exponentials, making me worried that just fixing the individual dtype mismatches will cause numeric issues.

title: [TF-TRT] Add Layout + ConstFold optimization on the TRT engine op
body:
### Motivation
The introduction of Tensor Cores in recent GPU architectures (and the subsequent changes in cuDNN) made `NHWC` the preferred layout for convolutions in TF.

However, the TensorRT API requires the input for convolution to be in `NCHW`. To satisfy this requirement, TF-TRT was inserting transpose ops around convolutions when necessary.

This PR adds a layout optimization pass with a target layout of `NCHW`, which ensures that most of Conv kernels will be in TRT compatible layout. Additionally, the layout optimization pass can eliminate redundant layout transpose operations. This results in a simpler TRT network with a larger potential for optimization.

### Description
TF-TRT now accomplishes it by running both a grapplers's `GenericLayoutOptimizer` followed by a ConstantFolding optimizers  in the `ConvertGraphDefToEngine`, applying them on a segment level.

The LayoutOptimizer ensures that the number of transposition is optimal. This optimization is described in slides 18-21 of [TensorFlow Graph Optimizations presentation ](https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs245/slides/TFGraphOptimizationsStanford.pdf)

This PR also modifies the `GenericLayoutOptimizer` to enforce a specific layout is set as layout target, through a ctor parameter.

The layout optimizer can be enabled with the environment variable `TF_TRT_ENABLE_LAYOUT_OPTIMIZER` (default=1, set to 0 to disable).

### Dependency

This PR needs the changes in https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/53368

I think C++14 as default was introduced here: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/f09d3e299752226f7a28c09a8e2018430b691a36

> Note on gcc version >=5: gcc uses the new C++ ABI since version 5. The binary pip packages available on the TensorFlow website are built with gcc4 that uses the older ABI. If you compile your op library with gcc>=5, add -D_GLIBCXX_USE_CXX11_ABI=0 to the command line to make the library compatible with the older abi.
